/-- A \emph{factorization} $f$ of a natural number $n$ is a function from the set of primes $\mathbb{P}$ to the non-negative integers $\mathbb{N}$ such that $\sum_{p \in \mathbb{P}} f(p) p = n$. We denote the set of all factorizations of $n$ by $\mathcal{F}_n$. The \emph{score} of a factorization $f$ with respect to a parameter $L$ is $\sum_{p \in \mathbb{P}} f(p) \log p$. The \emph{total imbalance} of a factorization $f$ is $\sum_{p \in \mathbb{P}} |f(p)|$. We say a factorization $f$ is \emph{balanced} if its total imbalance is 0.

We prove that for any natural number $n$, there exists a balanced factorization $f'$ of $n$ such that the score of $f'$ is at most the score of any other balanced factorization of $n$. Furthermore, we prove that the number of elements in this optimal balanced factorization is at most $\log n!$ plus the score of the original factorization, divided by $\log n$.

We also prove a more general result: given a parameter $M$, we construct an initial factorization whose score is small relative to $n$ and whose properties allow us to apply our first theorem to find an optimal balanced factorization. This initial factorization is obtained by taking the natural numbers between $n - n/M$ and $n$ repeated $M$ times, deleting those elements that are not $n/L$-smooth.

Let $P = (n, M, L, hL_pos, hL)$ be a set of parameters satisfying $L > 0$ and $n > L^2$. The initial factorization is defined as:

$$
a = \left( \text{replicate } M \left( \text{Ico } (n - n/M) \, n \right) \right). \text{filter} \left( \text{fun } m \Rightarrow m \in (n/L). \text{smoothNumbers} \right)
$$

where $\text{Ico } (A, B) = \{ x \in \mathbb{N} \mid A \leq x < B \}$.

We prove that the number of elements in this initial factorization is at most $n$. Furthermore, we prove that the total waste in this initial factorization is at most $n \log (1 - 1/M)^{-1}$.

We also prove that for primes $p > \sqrt{n}$, the $p$-adic valuation of $n!$ is $\lfloor n/p \rfloor$. For primes $p > \sqrt{n}$, we prove that a large prime $p > n/L$ cannot be in surplus. We prove that the total waste in the initial factorization is bounded by $n \log (1 - 1/M)^{-1}$. We prove that for primes $p > \sqrt{n}$, a large prime $p > n/L$ can be in deficit by at most $n/p$.

We prove bounds on the number of multiples of a prime $p$ in an interval. We prove that for primes $p > \sqrt{n}$, the sum of $p$-adic valuations in the initial factorization is bounded by $M$ times the count of multiples of $p$ in $[n - n/M, n)$.

We prove bounds on the $p$-adic valuations for various ranges of $p$:
- For $p > \sqrt{n}$ (large primes), the $p$-adic valuation is bounded by $M$.
- For $\sqrt{n} < p \leq n/L$ (medium primes), the $p$-adic valuation is bounded by $M$.
- For $L < p \leq \sqrt{n}$ (small primes), the $p$-adic valuation is bounded by $M \log n$.
- For $p \leq L$ (tiny primes), the $p$-adic valuation is bounded by $M \log n + ML\pi(n)$.

Finally, we prove that the score of the initial factorization is $o(n)$.

